1) git init --> create an empty local repository 
2) git config --global user.name "sushma"  (very First Time)  --> set userdetails
3) git config --global user.email "sushma.g@simplify3x.com" (Very First Time)  --> set userdetails
   git config --global --list  --> to verify
4) git status --> check the current state of local repository. (Current branch, Modified files, New (untracked) files, Staged files ready to commit, Whether your branch is ahead/behind the remote branch)
5) git add -A or git add .  --> adds all the files to staging area
   git add filename.java  --> add the specific file to staging area
   git add *.java  --> adds all the files which having the java extension
   git add foldername (src/test/java) --> adds all the files which is present in that particular folder
6) git commit -m "my api" ---> commits the tracked(staging) files to git repository (local)
Push the code to remote respository
7) git remote add origin "https://github.com/sushmaganji123/PetStoreAutomation.git" --> establishing the connection - local to remote repository (Very First Time) : Displays the remote repositories connected to the local repository.
   git remote -v  --> View connected remote repositories
8) git push -u origin main ---> Pushes the local main branch to the remote repository and sets the upstream (tracking) branch. After this, you can simply use git push.
   git push           --> Pushes the current branch to its configured remote tracking branch.
   git push --all origin   --> push the code to all the branches in remote respository
   git push origin --tags  --> push the code to all the tags
   git push origin v1.0  --> push to code to spectific tag
9) git clone <repository-url> --> Clone Repository from remote to local repository   
10) git pull origin main --> pull the code of remote repository from the main branch to local repository
11) git branch feature-api --> create the new branch
    git checkout feature-api or git switch feature-api --> switch to respective branch
    git branch --> View Branches
    git checkout -b feature-api  --> creates new branch and switch to that branch
12) git Merge feature-api --> Used to combine changes from one branch into another branch : First switch to the target branch then Merge feature-api into main then push the code to target branch only
13) git log --oneline or git log --> Displays commit history in a compact format. It helps quickly identify commits and commit IDs.
14) git diff ---> is used to compare file changes. It helps identify what modifications have been made before committing the code.
15) git stash --> the untracked files temporarily saved where can switch to branch and pull the laest code without losing the work
    git stash list --> shows the list of stash
    git stash pop -->restore and remove stash
    git stash apply --> restore and keep stash
16) git cherry-pick <commit-id> --> s used to apply a specific commit from one branch to another branch without merging the entire branch. It is commonly used for hotfixes and urgent production fixes.
    to get the commit-id : git log --online
 17) git push origin --delete feature-login --> Delete the respective branch in remote
 18) git branch -d feature-login ---> Delete the respective branch in local
 19) git branch -D feature-login ---> Delete the respective branch in local (Disable this message with "git config set advice.forceDeleteBranch false")

 A Pull Request (PR) is a code review mechanism used in GitHub, Azure DevOps, and Bitbucket.
 After completing development in a feature branch, we create a PR to merge the changes into the main or develop branch.
 Team members review the code, provide comments if necessary, and once approved, the PR is merged.
